segments.text: like i've just gone through a year of bad times and now i'm going to get to dish it out to somebody else and and i even as a freshman i began to think that that was a rather unprogressive attitude because the result of it i could see was that
that everybody wanted to add a little bit.

And, you know, and I could see that if the Corps went that direction that we were going to be, within a few years, we were going to be right back to the same state that had put them out at the Air Force base to start out with.
So anyway, the sophomores were usually more aggressive in hazing the freshmen than anybody else.
Did your official lady become a special friend?
Well, we were good friends before we went, but he decided that he was going to leave A&M after his, about halfway through his second semester at A&M.
And then not too long later, or before the semester was over, he decided he wanted to stay, but by then his grades had deteriorated to the point that he flunked out.
So he went away and,
I had not seen him since until about two years ago.
And I actually saw him for the first time.
He didn't transfer.
He didn't go somewhere else and make it up.
Well, eventually he went somewhere.
I think he went to a small Baptist school over in North Carolina or someplace and graduated over there.
Describe your room that freshman year.
What was in it?
How much time did y'all spend there at night and so forth?
Well, the, can we stop this for just a second?
So, we were in Milner Hall and so Milner was,
four stories but the first floor was slightly recessed below street level so I was in one of those lower rooms the windows opened right out onto almost onto a
flower bed or no flowers of course, but a sidewalk more or less.
Our room had two study desks.
It had a metal bunk bed, had closets, two closets.
We had space for our foot lockers and I guess that's all there was in that room.
And were you allowed to have your radio out on the table or?

You could have your radio out but you couldn't play it during call to quarters which was like from 7 in the evening until 10 and then you had a little time to get ready to go to bed and you had to go to bed unless you had a pass to stay up and study.
So I don't know when you could listen to the radio in the afternoon or something like that but you couldn't really use a radio during study period.
Now where were the restroom and shower facilities?
Well that building had them on each floor and so they were not too far away.
Did your outfit have the whole building?
Your company?
I think there was another company in that dorm.
It was the
Quartermaster Company.
And your outfit didn't have a nickname?
No.
No, we didn't.
How long was it before there were some jokes or pranks or good bull in the, in that dorm?
Those things started fairly early.
I'm just remembering that my freshman outfit was Company 11.
it was a combination of quartermaster people and transportation corps people.
And so later,
My sophomore year then, I was in a transportation corps, and then there was another unit that was the quartermaster company.
And so Murray Milford, who you know, was in that same unit with me.
And he went into the quartermaster company, and I went into the transportation corps.
Same freshman year?
Same freshman year.
But there were several high school athletes in our unit, and they were among the ones that began to get into the Good Bull first.
And then there were some other students.

I remember one in particular who I could pretty much tell from the beginning was not going to survive academically because he spent all of his time, you know, trying to dump water on somebody in the middle of the night or something like that.
And there was a sort of a negative correlation between how interested you were in Good Bull and whether or not you, you know, were passing all your courses or not.
The, when your outfit fell in, and was there, you marched to Sabeasa, which wasn't very far,
But did you ever, did they get the entire Corps together?
And if so, did you all have to march all the way to Duncan?
Well, we, I can't remember ever eating, as a freshman, I can't remember ever going to Duncan or ever marching over there.
We did have parades and, you know, the drill field now was the drill field then.
So then the Corps was called together there.
Right.
We would go there and there would be, I think it was Thursday afternoon, there was all our ROTC units had some kind of a drill activity and sometimes we'd end up on the
drill field there in front of where the MSC is.
How soon was it after you got here that you saw and heard the campus leaders, administrators, commandant, president, and so forth?
Well, we heard them the first week of orientation.
Who were they then?
Was Gilchrist the president?
I think he was.
I don't remember hearing him, but I remember, it seems like the commandant was Joe Davis, I think.
But I do remember hearing some of those people.
And then not too long after that, David Morgan was hired as the president of the college.
And I remember

I think as a sophomore, all of the core upperclassmen were called together and told that we were, you know, that this business of having the freshmen back in, they were going to put the freshmen back in the units.
And we were going to be the ones that would determine whether they would be successful or not or whether they'd have to abandon that.
And so I remember they made a real strong,
pitch for us to be responsible in the way we treated the freshmen.
When you went to class, what was your normal routine?
What did you take with you?
Where did you sit?
What was your game plan for academics?
Well, I remember as a high school graduate, I went and bought a kind of a
a briefcase like thing and as soon as I got here I figured out that that was a mistake and no one took more than one or two notebooks, spiral notebooks.
People usually didn't carry their textbooks to class and

uh you went to class and took notes in most classes that I was in we were assigned seats and the instructors checked roll based on which seats were empty and so you didn't have to worry about choosing where to sit or anything you know it was uh you just you got there I remember you know there were all kinds of stories about instructors that
that threw chalk at students that went to sleep and various things, you know.
I never did really see anything like that, I think.
I remember some classes that were pretty hard to stay awake in.
And did you pretty well spend your evening studying in your room?
As a freshman, yes.
You actually had to.
But you could go to the library if you got a pass or you could go study with somebody else if you got a pass.
But for some reason I really found more than I needed to do just to study by myself with my notes and books and everything.
And I do remember that we had quite a lot of homework and a lot of courses, you know, math problems to work.
I don't remember what else, but it seemed like that I was busy every afternoon and every night.
The Corps took up a huge amount of time being ready for the formation, shining shoes, shining brass, formations three meals a day, Yale practice two nights a week,
Midnight Yale practice if it was a home game, core trips, drill, and probably leaving out some other things, you know.
But there was just a big time burden involved in being in the course.
So by the time you did all that and then you prepared for your classes,
And I guess I really learned how to study as a freshman, you know, that I didn't really know that much about how to study as a high school student because I had a really easy time in high school.
How much did you communicate with your family back home that fall?
Do you remember?
Well, I wrote letters.
The only accessible long distance phones were in the MSC in a room near where the
where the hotel desk is now.
And I think I made two long distance phone calls that year.
I went home one, two, three times.
Three times during the- Thanksgiving, Christmas, Easter?
Well, four times.
Thanksgiving, Christmas, Easter, and between semesters.
And how often did somebody back home write you?
I remember getting letters from my mother, but they must not have come too often.
She was still teaching school and had two other kids at home.
But I remember writing letters and sending them home.
At that time, I was already dating the woman that I married to.
We dated all the way through my four years of dating.
So you wrote her some letters?
I wrote her some letters, and she wrote me some letters.
Where was she?
She was at Electra.
She was at Electra, okay.
Did you call her very often?
No, never.
She didn't have a telephone.
She lived out in the country, and they were away from where they could have a telephone.
And let's see, mailboxes were...
At the MSC or Northgate?
Both.
You can have one, I don't remember whether that was, I remember my first year I had one at the, I think I had one at the Northgate that year.
I guess you had some option about that and people tried to get at the MSC because they were going to go there anyway usually for something.
If we could read all of those letters you wrote that first year, do you think they would show optimism, increasing confidence in your ability to do the work?
I think so.
I guess after about the halfway through my freshman year, I really never had any doubt after that that I was going to
make it okay.
And you never seriously thought about transferring or dropping out?
No.
The, as the fall began, do you remember impressions of the first football game, some of the first traditions, rituals?
Well, those things have all sort of run together, but I

I can't really separate the first one from any of the others, but I remember the freshmen had certain things they had to do that no one else had to do during the games, and I remember being questioned about

who made which tackle or carried the ball on which occasion you know the next day and you were supposed to know everything you know if you didn't know what was the punishment uh just harassment you know it was mostly just verbal verbal harassment now with saturday classes there wasn't much time between your last class on saturday and falling in to eat and march to the game was there
That's right.

For day games, you could be due to formation for the game not too long after class, but I don't remember ever missing any meals, but I remember that they, you know, sort of adjusted the schedule in the dining halls for whatever we had to do.
Everything revolved around the schedule of the court.
What about the core trips that year?
Describe going on a core trip.
Well, I remember the freshman core trip.
One of the core trips would be either TCU or SMU.
And that year it was TCU.
And my parents came down and met us at the ball game.
And I think we went home with them after the game.
So that was a big treat.
How did you get to Fort Worth?
We hitchhiked.
That was just a real common thing in those days.
There were places out in front of the campus where students stood to catch rides.
And you had to have a little suitcase with an Aggie sticker on it and it was a more innocent time.
You know, people were not afraid to pick up hitchhikers.
Did you ever have, I presume you hitchhiked for four years?
No, but I hitchhiked a lot that first year.
My second year, I got a car.
Oh, okay.
In all of your hitchhiking, did you ever have a negative experience?
Yeah, I was picked up by a homosexual one time who was rather aggressive and I finally just told him to let me out.
And that was, I guess that was, you know, happened to more than one student.
I've had a couple of others and those are the only negative other than somebody maybe driving a little too fast,
maybe having had another beer too many, but nothing else?
Nobody trying to rob anybody or anything like that?
No, I was picked up by somebody that had been drinking too much one time.
He was driving a truck and he drove us away and then he decided he needed something else to drink and my roommate was with me at the time.
We were together.
We decided we were going to look for another ride and we found another ride.
And there was almost
an unwritten directory of where were the best places to go, to stand in almost every town, weren't there?
Yes.
There were, you know, at Waco, for example, and at Fort Worth, there were places you were supposed to go, and you were not supposed to upstream those places.
You weren't supposed to get closer to town than wherever that place was.
Now, there wasn't any written direct list of those, were there?
No.
That was all just the...
the Aggie lower that was passed on from class to class.
Now did the special young lady come down to Fort Worth that fall?
I can't remember.
Seems like that she came to that game at Fort Worth.
And how did you feel as you were marching with the Corps for the first time somewhere else that day in Fort Worth?
How did you feel about A&M and so forth?
Well, I felt very proud to be representing A&M and to be in that group of people.
I thought basically that it was a good group of people.
We had the impression that we didn't have a good reputation in the state, that people thought we were ruffians.
used too much bad language and drank too much and everything.
You know, I didn't really do either and I knew a lot of people that didn't do either and I felt like, you know, that it was a good group of people.
Uh, and was there any verbal abuse had thrown at the Corps as you all marched down?
Not that I remember.
I haven't heard of anybody with that either.
No.
And so you were with your family and then you hitchhiked back the next day?
Yes, it had to be the next day.
So we went home Saturday night and by two o'clock on Sunday we had to start back.
About how long did it take you to hitchhike from Iowa Park to, or Wichita Falls to College Station?
Well if you left at two o'clock on
on Sunday afternoon and you were lucky you'd be back by 8 or 10 o'clock at night, you know.
But I remember one time getting back about 2 o'clock in the morning.
Now did you come through Fort Worth down to Waco?
Yes.
And then came Highway 6 from there.
Other A&M traditions, do you remember going to Silver Taps?
Oh yes that was I remember silver caps and I remember the muster that year muster was a strange experience that year because the Korean War was going on you know and they were already described
They were already reporting people that were here the year before that were killed since they had graduated and so that was, I remember that was a moving experience.
And Muster was then held on the MSC steps or in Guyon?
It seems like it was in Guyon that year.
Okay.
uh and uh what about bonfire your freshman year did you work on bonfire i worked on bonfire but i had a it was it was really a hard experience because uh uh

We not only moved all the logs from where they were cut to load them on the trucks, but we did all the loading by hand and all of the standing up of the logs at the bonfire was done with ropes and pulleys over the top of the bonfire.

everything so and it I don't remember it it seemed like it lasted for quite some length of time you know not just a week or so and uh so eventually I began to think of I need to study this afternoon instead of work on that bonfire and I had a a classmate in one of my classes who was not in the corps and he had a room in the old
a building called Post Graduate Hall, which was behind Walton Hall.
And so I would two or three evenings or afternoons during the
later stages of Bonfire.
I just went over there and sat around and studied and kept from working every minute.
But Bonfire was a big experience all of my four years.
That effort your freshman year, was it say a month or longer than that?
It's probably about a month.
And bonfire was held on the drill field?
On the right in front of the MSC.
And do you remember any accident?
Did anybody get hurt or break a leg or cut anything badly?
I don't remember.
I don't remember seeing anything.
I remember that during those four years there may have been a few axe cuts or things, but that's all I remember.
Larry, go home Thanksgiving, and what did you tell people about A&M and how you were doing?
Do you remember?
No, I don't.
I don't particularly remember.
I do remember that I took my uniform and wore it.
I remember, you know, not having any hair and how I embarrassed my wife.
My wife now was, you know, for me to show up, you know, just slick-headed as could be.
And, but you, you in no way were, were headed away or anything like that.
Then you go home Christmas and you get, and your first semester ends academically doing pretty well.
Yes.
Over a two point.
Well, in today's lingo, it would have been over a three.
Right, yeah.
And your toughest courses were what, in terms of making the grades?
Well, my lowest grades were in English, which was interesting.
when I eventually became a scientist and my whole career was hinging on my ability to speak and my ability to write.
But, you know, those guys taught me well enough, you know, that I was equipped.
I guess other than that, I don't remember ever really struggling with anything.
struggling to make an A instead of a B.
And so that was, you know, that's where most of my work was done was trying to get my grade high enough to get an A in a course.
Alright, you go home after your freshman year.
What did you do that summer?
I believe that was the summer that I was a, I think, that probably was the summer that I mowed right of ways for the highway department.
So my father had a tractor.
In that area?
In that area.
So we were sort of contractors.
What kind of pay did he get, do you remember?
Well with me and the tractor and the mower and all of the maintenance on the mowing apparatus we got ten dollars an hour.
And uh.. That's pretty good pay wasn't it for that era?
Right.
My father, well you know we had to keep the tractor going and the gas and everything.
But that was quite a lot of money.
So we split that.
We put five dollars
per hour back into the tractor and I got $5 an hour.
Do you remember what a year here cost you in round numbers?
My mother had money saved for my education.
She was one of nine children, all but one, all of them went to college.
That was.
A very unusual family.
Not all of them graduated, you know.
Some of them graduated from two-year institutions.
I think one of them didn't go but one year.
But all of them but one taught at some time in their life.
So mother had, at great personal sacrifice, had saved money for me to go to school and for the other, my brother and sister too.
And so I had $1,000 for the first year, for each year actually.
And I remember that I had a couple of hundred dollars left when the year was over.
So it was about $800.
What did you, for your spending money, what did you spend it on while you were here?
We had an early meal on Sunday evening that was always cold cuts.
And so that was sort of either Saturday evening or Sunday evening, it was not too unusual for guys to go out and eat someplace off campus.
And that was about it.
I can't remember.
Where did, if you did, where did you eat?
Well there was a very limited number of places but I remember there was a grocery store in North Bryan called Wehrman's that was had a sort of a auxiliary dining room there and we went there a lot.
We went to uh it was kind of a general restaurant at North Gate and I can't remember the name of it uh a lot of guys went to a
restaurant at the building still there called Youngbloods.
I guess I went there a few times.
We would go to Kelly's in downtown Bryan and Hotart's Cafeteria and Kelly's was a hotel coffee shop I think and
There were two or three drive-ins on College Avenue.
The Texan was a drive-in, and there was another one, I don't remember what the name of it was, but there were... Was Martin's BBQ going then?
I believe it was, but it had the aura of being more of a beer joint than a food place, at least to me, I don't know.
I know that you were not a drinker.
Did you have any personal policy that if they served alcohol, you didn't go?
No.
No, I didn't that, but there were some places that you just had the impression that the food service was totally secondary.
Now, was Uncle Ed's going in that Hard Liquors?
I'm not sure I know.
Down Welborn Road?
I don't know exactly when it was there.
I don't remember that at all.
It was a Czech man.
